Request to expose the cfitsio routine [fits_get_hduaddrll](https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/software/fitsio/c/c_user/node65.html) to the Python interface. Suggested usage:

    (header_start, data_start, data_end) = some_file.byte_offsets(hdu=i)

Glue code (untested!!) below:

```
static PyObject *
PyFITSObject_get_hduaddr(PyObject* self, PyObject* args) {

	// arguments
	int hdunum;

	// cfitsio variables
	int status = 0;
	long long header_start;
	long long data_start;
	long long data_end;
	
	if (self->fits == NULL) {
       PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError, "fits file is NULL");
       return NULL;
   }

   if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, (char*)"i", &hdunum)) {
       return NULL;
   }

	// move to specified HDU
	if (fits_movabs_hdu(self->file, hdunum, NULL, &status)) {
		set_ioerr_string_from_status(status);
		return NULL;
	}

	// get byte offsets
	if (fits_get_hduaddrll(self->file, &header_start, &data_start, &data_end, &status)) {
		set_ioerr_string_from_status(status);
		return NULL;
	}
	
	// return values as tuple: (header_start, data_start, data_end)
	PyObject* offsets = PyTuple_New(3);
	PyTuple_SetItem(offsets, 0, PyLong_FromLongLong(header_start));
	PyTuple_SetItem(offsets, 1, PyLong_FromLongLong(data_start));
	PyTuple_SetItem(offsets, 2, PyLong_FromLongLong(data_end));
	
	return offsets;
}
```

The ADFS server I am working with is sending a reference URI like "#_639146ac-a51f-44a3-8a2d-c2c4d944c7d3". However, the element it is referring to is identified by an "AssertionID" attribute, instead of just "ID".

Here is the workaround I'm using right now:

    from signxml import xmldsig, InvalidInput

    class ADFSAssertionDSig(xmldsig):
    
        def _resolve_reference(self, doc_root, reference, uri_resolver=None):
            try:
                return xmldsig._resolve_reference(self, doc_root, reference, uri_resolver)
            except InvalidInput:
                return self._resolve_reference_by_assertion_id_attribute(doc_root, reference, uri_resolver)
    
        def _resolve_reference_by_assertion_id_attribute(self, doc_root, reference, uri_resolver=None):
            uri = reference.get("URI")
            results = doc_root.xpath("..//*[@AssertionId=$uri]", uri=uri.lstrip("#"))
            if len(results) < 1:
                results += doc_root.xpath("..//*[@AssertionID=$uri]", uri=uri.lstrip("#"))
            if len(results) < 1:
                raise InvalidInput("Unable to resolve reference URI: {}".format(uri))
            return results[0]

I'm thinking there should be a more elegant solution.

BTW, I thanks for the Python 3 fixes. I was actually working on a pull request last weekend for that, only to see on Monday that you had got it done.

Given the following code snippet there's no completion after `subprocess.`.

This is triggered by having an inline function before it, and the import not at the top of the file.

    class Writer():
        def write(self):
            def foo():
                pass

            import subprocess
            subprocess.



It works with this:

    import subprocess

    class Writer():
        def write(self):
            def foo():
                pass

            subprocess.

This also works:

    class Writer():
        def write(self):
            import subprocess
            subprocess.

I am using jedi-vim and jedi 7b50bb0.  I have not tested it outside of jedi-vim.

This results from the help command's context preventing the use of `ctx.cog`.

Here's a minimal example that demostrates the issue. When the help formatter is called, ctx.cog is None so an exception is thrown. It would be nice to have a way to access the "original" cog. I checked the rewrite branch too and there didn't seem to be a way to do this yet.

(Also possible feature request: cog-wide checks)

```
from discord.ext import commands

def is_authorized():
    def predicate(ctx):
        return ctx.message.author.id in ctx.cog.admin_user_ids:

    return commands.check(predicate)

class Admin:
    """
    Commands available for admins only
    """

    def __init__(self, bot, admin_user_ids):
        self.bot = bot
        self.admin_user_ids = admin_user_ids

    @commands.command()
    @is_authorized()
    async def hey(self):
        await self.bot.reply("Hey!")

```
