In some usage scenario, user doesn't need to know the exact contact point of the collision. Thus, it's happy if the user could got 50% performance improved through just rewrite the default near callback.

```C++
# collisionPair.m_algorithm->processCollision(&obj0Wrap,&obj1Wrap,dispatchInfo,&contactPointResult);
collisionPair.m_algorithm->processCollision(&obj0Wrap,&obj1Wrap,dispatchInfo);
collisionPair.m_algorithm->processManifoldResult(&obj0Wrap,&obj1Wrap,dispatchInfo,&contactPointResult);
```

A benchmark profile of bullet2:
![test](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/652101/6684413/ffc00e94-cccb-11e4-83bf-14feff820b97.png)

graphene==1.1.3
graphql-core==1.0.1
graphql-relay==0.4.5

graphql-core requires a non-null root query for introspection

https://github.com/graphql-python/graphql-core/blob/dadb918764fc95b33d31577e11fd08323b59b081/graphql/type/introspection.py#L41

https://github.com/facebook/graphql/issues/218 revolves around determining why the spec requires a root query, but for now it appears that it is non-nullable.

https://github.com/facebook/graphql/blob/e1dd45286e83cea73b7b071dc14e9f4dc5208ace/spec/Section%204%20--%20Introspection.md#schema-introspection

Example
```
class Test(ClientIDMutation):
    class Input(object):
        x = InputField(String)

    x = Field(String)

    @classmethod
    def mutate_and_get_payload(cls, args, context, _info):
        return cls(x=args['x'])


class Mutation(ObjectType):
    test = Test.Field()


schema = Schema(query=None, mutation=Mutation)
```

unicode(schema)
```
schema {
  mutation: Mutation
}

type Mutation {
  test(input: TestInput!): TestPayload
}

input TestInput {
  x: String
  clientMutationId: String
}

type TestPayload {
  x: String
  clientMutationId: String
}
```

json.dumps(schema.introspect())
```
null
```
---
1. You should not be able to do `Schema(query=None)` without an error.
